# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# sleepctl dashboard — environment configuration
#
# Copy this file to .env before running `make up`:
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# `make up` does that copy automatically if .env doesn't exist, and will
# also auto-generate a strong DASHBOARD_PASSWORD if it is still "changeme".
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Auth ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Single-user credentials for the dashboard login.
# `make up` replaces the placeholder password with a random one on first run.
DASHBOARD_USER=admin
DASHBOARD_PASSWORD=changeme

# JWT signing secret.  Leave blank to auto-generate on first container start;
# the secret is then persisted to the `sleepdata` volume at /data/.jwt_secret
# so it survives restarts.  You may set an explicit value here if you prefer
# full control (run: python3 -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_hex(32))").
JWT_SECRET=

# ── CORS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Comma-separated list of allowed origins for the FastAPI CORS middleware.
# "*" is fine for a local-only deployment.  If you add a public tunnel
# (Tailscale / Cloudflare) add its origin here.
CORS_ORIGINS=*

# ── Timezone ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Set to your local zone so sleep-window timestamps display correctly.
# Examples: America/New_York  America/Los_Angeles  Europe/London  Asia/Tokyo
TZ=America/New_York

# ── Optional: database path override ─────────────────────────────────────────
# Defaults to /data/sleepctl.db inside the container (backed by the sleepdata
# named volume).  Only change this if you want to mount a host path instead.
# SLEEPCTL_DB=/data/sleepctl.db

# ── Optional: JWT lifetime ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How long a login session stays valid (hours).  Default: 720 (30 days),
# which keeps you logged in on iPhone for a month without re-entering the PIN.
# JWT_TTL_HOURS=720

# ── Live Eight Sleep Pod control (optional) ──────────────────────────────────
# By default the control daemon runs in SIMULATOR mode (no real device needed).
# To drive your actual Pod, set SLEEPCTL_LIVE=1 and provide your Eight Sleep
# account credentials below.  See deploy/LIVE_POD.md for the full bring-up.
#
# IMPORTANT: keep SLEEPCTL_DRY_RUN=1 for the first night or two — the daemon then
# reads real physiology and logs its decisions but sends NO commands to the bed.
# Set it to 0 once you're happy with what it would do.

# SLEEPCTL_LIVE=0
# SLEEPCTL_DRY_RUN=1

# Your Eight Sleep app login (the same email/password you use in the mobile app).
# EIGHTSLEEP_EMAIL=you@example.com
# EIGHTSLEEP_PASSWORD=your-eight-sleep-password
# EIGHTSLEEP_SIDE=left            # left | right (your side of the bed)
# EIGHTSLEEP_TIMEZONE=America/New_York

# Some newer Eight Sleep accounts require an OAuth2 client id/secret. If plain
# email/password fails to authenticate, see deploy/LIVE_POD.md for how to obtain
# these, then set them here.
# EIGHTSLEEP_CLIENT_ID=
# EIGHTSLEEP_CLIENT_SECRET=

# ── Optional: work-shift calendar (auto-connect without the dashboard UI) ─────
# Paste your dedicated work-shift calendar's "Secret address in iCal format" from
# Google Calendar (Settings → Integrate calendar). On startup it auto-connects the
# feed so day/night shifts drive the wake alarm + banking planner. Kept only in this
# gitignored file; the app stores it locally and masks it — never commit a real URL.
# If you later change/disconnect it in the dashboard, that wins over this on reboot.
# CALENDAR_ICS_URL=https://calendar.google.com/calendar/ical/.../basic.ics

# ── Optional: token-less phone-sensor ingest (trusted LAN only) ───────────────
# Drops auth on the phone endpoints ONLY (/bcg/ingest, /bcg/should-record) so an
# iPhone running Sensor Logger can stream with no token / no Auth Header. Every
# other endpoint stays login-protected. Enable this ONLY when the API is reached
# on your home network and is NOT exposed to the open internet.
# To reach the API directly from the phone at http://<server-ip>:8000, also
# publish the port — add `ports: ["8000:8000"]` to the `api` service in
# docker-compose.yml (it's unpublished by default; Caddy is the only ingress).
# BCG_INGEST_OPEN=1

# ── Optional: static ingest token for the phone endpoints (funnel-safe) ───────
# A static, non-expiring shared secret the phone passes as ?token=<value> on
# /bcg/ingest and /bcg/should-record. UNLIKE BCG_INGEST_OPEN (which drops auth
# entirely), this keeps ingest AUTHENTICATED even over the public Tailscale
# funnel — and unlike the 30-day dashboard JWT, it never expires, so there's no
# token to re-mint on the phone every month. Recommended when the API is exposed
# to the internet. Generate a strong value with:
#   python -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_urlsafe(24))"
# This file is gitignored — NEVER commit a real value.
# BCG_INGEST_TOKEN=

# ── Optional: dedicated BLE heart-rate sensor (Polar Verity Sense) ────────────
# A Polar Verity Sense armband (or H10 chest strap) gives clean HR + beat-to-beat HRV that the
# controller uses as the AUTHORITATIVE cardiac signal, MERGED with the iPhone's movement — the
# physiology path that works even when the Pod's own sleep tracking is unavailable. Run
# scripts/verity_forwarder.py on this PC (it reads BCG_INGEST_TOKEN above for auth), or set
# SLEEPCTL_VERITY=1 so the watchdog auto-launches it. See deploy/VERITY_SENSOR.md. Optionally
# pin the sensor's BLE address to skip auto-discovery:
# SLEEPCTL_VERITY=1
# SLEEPCTL_VERITY_ADDRESS=AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF

# ── Optional: Web Push (critical alerts -> phone) ────────────────────────────
# When the controller goes down / thermal control stalls / the tank runs dry, the
# dashboard raises an in-app alert immediately either way (Alerts tab / GET /alerts).
# Setting these ALSO pushes a phone notification for newly-appearing CRITICAL issues,
# even if nobody has the dashboard tab open — see dashboard/api/app/push_sender.py.
#
# Generate a keypair (requires the optional `pywebpush` package — see
# dashboard/api/requirements.txt):
#   pip install pywebpush && python -m app.push_keys
# Paste the two printed lines below. NEVER commit real keys — this file only ships the
# placeholder; your actual `.env` is gitignored.
# VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=
# VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY=
# VAPID_SUBJECT=mailto:you@example.com

# ── Optional: off-box dead-man's-switch (healthchecks.io or similar) ─────────
# scripts/windows-watchdog.ps1's supervise loop POSTs a ping here once per cycle, but ONLY when
# api + daemon + web are ALL locally healthy. If the box loses power/network, or a component is
# up but broken, pings simply stop -- configure the healthchecks.io check's "grace period" (e.g.
# a few minutes) and it will alert you by email/SMS/push on a MISSED ping, catching both "box is
# dark" and "box is up but broken" with one mechanism, from off-box, with no server to maintain.
# Leaving this unset is a clean no-op (the watchdog just skips the ping silently).
# HEALTHCHECKS_URL=https://hc-ping.com/<your-uuid-here>

# ── Optional: off-box ENCRYPTED database backup ───────────────────────────────
# The code repo is PUBLIC, but the SQLite DB holds months of personal physiology
# (HR/HRV/sleep stages/presence). scripts/backup-encrypted.ps1 age-encrypts a daily
# snapshot and pushes the ciphertext to the repo's dedicated `db-backups` branch --
# the blob is world-readable but useless without the private key, which never lives
# on this laptop. Paste the age PUBLIC key (starts "age1...") printed by `age-keygen`
# during the one-time setup in deploy/BACKUP_SETUP.md. Leaving this unset just means
# the offsite step logs "not configured" and exits cleanly (local rotation still runs).
# BACKUP_AGE_RECIPIENT=age1...

# ── Optional: GitHub push token (health snapshot + offsite backup) ────────────
# scripts/publish-health.ps1 (operational health -> `health` branch) and
# scripts/backup-encrypted.ps1 (encrypted DB -> `db-backups` branch) PUSH to this repo.
# On Windows the watchdog's Scheduled Task runs as a different user than your interactive
# login, so a browser/Git-Credential-Manager login (which is per-user) is invisible to the
# background pushes and they fail. Set a token here and both scripts push with it regardless
# of which user runs them. Use a FINE-GRAINED PAT scoped to ONLY this repo with
# Contents: Read and write (github.com -> Settings -> Developer settings -> Fine-grained
# tokens). Kept only in this gitignored file; never commit a real value. Leaving it unset
# falls back to whatever credential the running user happens to have.
# GIT_PUSH_TOKEN=github_pat_...
